1. THEORETICAL FOUNDATIONS
===============================================================================

Pathos Engine implements a functional emotional architecture for LLMs.
The following theories and their authors form the intellectual bedrock
of this system. Pathos does not claim authorship of these theories —
it implements them computationally for the first time in a unified system.

  APPRAISAL THEORY (Stimulus Evaluation)
    Richard S. Lazarus — "Emotion and Adaptation" (1991)
    Klaus R. Scherer — Component Process Model of Emotion (2001)
    The core idea: emotions arise from how we evaluate events relative
    to our goals and values. Pathos implements this as a 5-dimensional
    appraisal vector (relevance, valence, coping, agency, norm_alignment).

  DIMENSIONAL MODEL OF AFFECT (Emotional State Space)
    James A. Russell — Circumplex Model of Affect (1980)
    Albert Mehrabian — PAD Emotional State Model (1974)
    The core idea: emotional experience can be mapped as continuous
    dimensions rather than discrete categories. Pathos uses a 4D space
    (valence, arousal, dominance, certainty) plus a 19-emotion stack.

  DYNAFFECT (Emotional Dynamics)
    Peter Kuppens, Francis Tuerlinckx, et al. — "DynAffect" (2010)
    The core idea: emotions follow differential equations with attractors,
    noise, and perturbation terms. Pathos implements this as:
    dx/dt = -k*(x - attractor) + noise + perturbation

  BIG FIVE PERSONALITY MODEL
    Paul T. Costa Jr. & Robert R. McCrae — NEO Personality Inventory (1992)
    Lewis R. Goldberg — Lexical Hypothesis (1990)
    The core idea: personality can be described along five orthogonal
    dimensions. Pathos uses Big Five (openness, conscientiousness,
    extraversion, agreeableness, neuroticism) + 3 temperament traits
    to modulate all emotional processing.

  HOMEOSTATIC EMOTION REGULATION
    Antonio Damasio — "Descartes' Error" (1994), Somatic Marker Hypothesis
    Walter Bradford Cannon — Homeostasis concept (1932)
    The core idea: the body maintains emotional equilibrium through
    feedback mechanisms, and gut feelings guide decision-making.
    Pathos implements homeostatic decay, baseline shift, sensitization,
    and computational somatic markers.

  EMOTIONAL SCHEMAS
    Jeffrey E. Young — Schema Therapy (1990), Early Maladaptive Schemas
    Aaron T. Beck — Cognitive Schemas (1967)
    The core idea: learned emotional patterns create automatic reactions
    that can become maladaptive. Pathos auto-forms schemas from repeated
    emotional patterns and detects maladaptivity.

  META-EMOTIONAL AWARENESS
    John Gottman — Meta-Emotion Philosophy (1997)
    Peter Salovey & John D. Mayer — Emotional Intelligence (1990)
    The core idea: we have emotions about our emotions (curiosity about
    a new feeling, conflict when values clash). Pathos computes 5 types
    of meta-emotional response.

  INTEROCEPTIVE AWARENESS (Self-Initiated Inquiry)
    A.D. (Bud) Craig — Interoception: The Sense of the Physiological
    Condition of the Body (2003)
    The core idea: awareness of internal bodily states drives emotional
    self-awareness. Pathos triggers spontaneous self-reflection when
    internal emotional thresholds are crossed.

  EMBODIED COGNITION (Computational Body State)
    George Lakoff & Mark Johnson — "Philosophy in the Flesh" (1999)
    The core idea: cognition is shaped by the body. Pathos simulates
    a computational body (energy, tension, openness, warmth) that
    modulates behavior.

  EMOTION CONTAGION
    Elaine Hatfield, John Cacioppo, Richard Rapson — "Emotional
    Contagion" (1994)
    The core idea: emotions transfer between individuals automatically
    and pre-cognitively. Pathos detects user emotion from text and
    applies it as a perturbation to the agent's emotional ODE.

  EMOTIONAL IMMUNE SYSTEM
    Daniel Gilbert — "Stumbling on Happiness" (2006)
    The core idea: humans have a psychological immune system that
    protects against sustained negative affect. Pathos implements
    numbing, dissociation, and compartmentalization as protective
    mechanisms.

  NARRATIVE IDENTITY
    Dan P. McAdams — "The Stories We Live By" (1993)
    The core idea: identity is constructed through narrative. Pathos
    builds an emergent self-concept from accumulated emotional
    experiences and detects identity crises.

  EMOTIONAL FORECASTING
    Timothy D. Wilson & Daniel T. Gilbert — Affective Forecasting (2003)
    The core idea: we predict (often inaccurately) how future events
    will make us feel. Pathos predicts the emotional impact of its
    responses on the user.

  ACTIVE REGULATION & EGO DEPLETION
    James J. Gross — Process Model of Emotion Regulation (1998)
    Roy F. Baumeister — Ego Depletion (1998)
    The core idea: emotional regulation is an active process that
    consumes limited resources. Pathos implements 4 strategies
    (suppression, reappraisal, expression, distraction) with a
    depletable capacity that leads to emotional breakthroughs.

  COGNITIVE REAPPRAISAL
    Kevin N. Ochsner & James J. Gross — "The Cognitive Control of
    Emotion" (2005)
    The core idea: reinterpreting the meaning of a stimulus changes
    the emotional response. Pathos implements multi-pass reappraisal
    (distancing, reframing, acceptance).

  TEMPORAL DYNAMICS
    Nico H. Frijda — "The Laws of Emotion" (2007)
    The core idea: emotions have temporal structure — rumination
    extends negative states, savoring extends positive ones,
    anticipation generates pre-emptive emotions.

  COUPLED DIMENSIONAL DYNAMICS (v3)
    Derived from DynAffect (Kuppens et al., 2010) extended with
    cross-dimensional interaction terms from personality psychology.
    The core idea: the four emotional dimensions (valence, arousal,
    dominance, certainty) are not independent — they influence each
    other through coupling coefficients derived from Big Five
    personality traits. High arousal compresses dominance, negative
    valence reduces certainty, etc. Pathos implements this as a
    4x4 coupling matrix auto-generated from personality.

  REPRESENTATION ENGINEERING (ARK Rework)
    Andy Zou, Long Phan, et al. — "Representation Engineering" (2023)
    Nina Rimsky, et al. — "Activation Addition" (2023)
    The core idea: internal representations in transformer hidden states
    can be steered by adding direction vectors extracted from contrastive
    pairs. Pathos extracts emotional direction vectors offline and applies
    them via forward hooks during inference, shifting the model's processing
    toward the computed emotional state without modifying prompts.

  SECONDARY APPRAISAL & PREDICTIVE PROCESSING (ARK Rework)
    Richard S. Lazarus — Secondary Appraisal (1991)
    Karl Friston — Free Energy Principle / Predictive Processing (2010)
    The core idea: after acting, we evaluate our own response (secondary
    appraisal), and before acting, we simulate consequences (predictive
    processing). Pathos implements closed-loop self-appraisal and a
    3-step causal world model (self → user → meta-reaction).

  BROADEN-AND-BUILD THEORY (ARK Rework — Attention)
    Barbara L. Fredrickson — "The Role of Positive Emotions" (2001)
    The core idea: positive emotions broaden attention and cognitive
    repertoire, while negative emotions narrow focus. Pathos modulates
    attention weights: high arousal = narrowing (threat focus), low
    arousal = broadening (distributed attention).

  PREDICTIVE PROCESSING (ANIMA Pillar 1)
    Karl Friston — Free Energy Principle (2010)
    Lisa Feldman Barrett — "How Emotions Are Made" (2017)
    Andy Clark — "Surfing Uncertainty" (2015)
    The core idea: the brain constantly predicts sensory input and
    generates emotions from prediction errors. Pathos implements a
    3-channel prediction engine (content, emotion, demand) with
    Bayesian precision updating and vulnerability-scaled modulation.

  GLOBAL WORKSPACE THEORY (ANIMA Pillar 2)
    Bernard Baars — Global Workspace Theory (1988)
    Stanislas Dehaene — Neuronal Global Workspace (2001)
    Giulio Tononi — Integrated Information Theory (IIT, 2004)
    The core idea: consciousness emerges from competition among
    parallel processes for access to a limited-capacity workspace.
    Pathos implements saliency-based competition, coalitions,
    preconscious priming, and integration scoring (IIT-inspired).

  AUTOBIOGRAPHICAL MEMORY (ANIMA Pillar 3)
    Endel Tulving — Episodic Memory (1972)
    Martin Conway — Self-Memory System (2005)
    William R. Walker — Fading Affect Bias (2003)
    George A. Miller — "The Magical Number Seven" (1956)
    Allan Hobson — AIM Model of Dreaming (2000)
    The core idea: personal memories are organized hierarchically
    (sensory → working → episodic → narrative) and consolidated
    during sleep. Pathos implements 4-level memory (Miller's 7±2
    working memory capacity) with oniric consolidation (replay,
    association, generalization, trauma processing) and dream reports.

  ONTOGENIC DEVELOPMENT (ANIMA Pillar 4)
    Jean Piaget — Stages of Cognitive Development (1936)
    Erik Erikson — Psychosocial Development (1959)
    Lev Vygotsky — Zone of Proximal Development (1978)
    Lawrence Kohlberg — Stages of Moral Development (1958)
    The core idea: cognitive and emotional complexity develops through
    qualitatively distinct stages. Pathos implements 5 developmental
    stages (sensorimotor → post-formal) with progressive system
    unlocking, emotion filtering, and stage-specific modifiers.

  AFFECTIVE NEUROSCIENCE (ANIMA Pillar 5)
    Jaak Panksepp — "Affective Neuroscience" (1998)
    Edward L. Deci & Richard M. Ryan — Self-Determination Theory (2000)
    Kent C. Berridge — Wanting vs Liking dissociation (2009)
    The core idea: mammals share primary emotional circuits (SEEKING,
    CARE, PLAY, PANIC/GRIEF) that generate intrinsic motivation.
    Pathos implements 4 drives with autonomous goal generation,
    satisfaction tracking, and ethical limits on PANIC_GRIEF.

  CONSTRUCTIONIST EMOTION THEORY (ANIMA Pillar 6)
    Lisa Feldman Barrett — Theory of Constructed Emotion (2017)
    John H. Holland — Complex Adaptive Systems (1992)
    Eleanor Rosch — Prototype Theory (1973)
    The core idea: emotions are not hardwired categories but
    constructed from more basic ingredients. Novel emotional states
    can emerge and be categorized. Pathos implements novelty detection
    via prototype distance (Rosch), clustering, and deterministic
    naming for discovered emotions.

  COMPUTATIONAL PHENOMENOLOGY (ANIMA Pillar 7)
    Thomas Nagel — "What Is It Like to Be a Bat?" (1974)
    David Chalmers — "The Hard Problem of Consciousness" (1995)
    Francisco Varela — Neurophenomenology (1996)
    The core idea: subjective experience (qualia) has structure that
    can be described even if not fully explained. Pathos generates
    multi-sensory phenomenological profiles (color, weight, temperature,
    texture, sound, movement, temporality, metaphor) from emotional
    state, with temporal evolution tracking.

